$\begin{aligned} & \text { [ Arithmetic. Mental calculation, etc. } \\ & \text { [ Problems with inequalities. Case analysis ] }\end{aligned}$

In the olympiad, 2006 schoolchildren participated. It turned out that Vasya, a schoolboy, solved only one out of six problems, and the number of participants who solved

at least 1 problem is 4 times greater than those who solved at least 2;

at least 2 problems is 4 times greater than those who solved at least 3;

at least 3 problems is 4 times greater than those who solved at least 4;

at least 4 problems is 4 times greater than those who solved at least 5;

at least 5 problems is 4 times greater than those who solved all 6.

How many schoolchildren did not solve any problems?

Problem 1. Consider $A \in \mathcal{M}_{2020}(\mathbb{C})$ such that

$$
\begin{aligned}
& A+A^{\times}=I_{2020} \\
& A \cdot A^{\times}=I_{2020}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $A^{\times}$is the adjugate matrix of $A$, i.e., the matrix whose elements are $a_{i j}=(-1)^{i+j} d_{j i}$, where $d_{j i}$ is the determinant obtained from $A$, eliminating the line $j$ and the column $i$.

Find the maximum number of matrices verifying (1) such that any two of them are not similar.
